Just for the record, the term for  geometry is Hyperbolic Space.

The confusion over the name actually goes back to the early 1900's: In Lovecraft's day, non-euclidean geometry did just mean  (that doesn't follow one or more of the rules of normal euclidean geometry), but they've since formalized and subdivided the field, and now it just refers to curved spaces- elliptical if parallel lines can converge, and hyperbolic if they can diverge.







